# logs-sink — central audit log pipeline

This is a **companion** Lakeflow Spark Declarative Pipeline that tails
`/logz` from every Databricks App in the workspace and writes structured
audit events into a single Delta table:

```
{{.audit_catalog}}.audit.app_events
```

You deploy it **once per workspace**, not per app. Every app in the org
emits JSON via `AuditLoggerMiddleware` and shows up here.

## What you get

| Column | Type | Source |
|---|---|---|
| `ts` | TIMESTAMP | middleware |
| `app` | STRING | middleware (`APP_NAME` env) |
| `user` | STRING | `x-forwarded-email` |
| `method` | STRING | request |
| `path` | STRING | request |
| `status` | INT | response |
| `ms` | DOUBLE | latency |
| `type` | STRING | classified: `data_access`, `data_edit`, `permission_deny`, `authentication` |
| `error` | STRING | exception message if any |
| `_ingest_ts` | TIMESTAMP | pipeline ingest time |

Use cases:

- "Who accessed patient X in the last 30 days?" — SELECT on `user`, `path`.
- "Show me every permission_deny for app Y this week." — SELECT on `type`.
- Auto-alert on >N permission_deny events per app per hour.

## Deploy

```bash
cd logs-sink
databricks bundle deploy -t prod
databricks pipelines start --pipeline-id <id-from-deploy-output>
```

The pipeline is serverless and continuous. It will pick up new apps
automatically the next time they emit logs — there is no per-app config.

## Source

The pipeline reads from the Apps system table:
`system.access.app_request_logs` (where `/logz` is materialized) and
parses the JSON column written by `AuditLoggerMiddleware`. If your
workspace does not have this system table enabled, ask the workspace
admin to enable system schemas for `access` and `serving`.
